<subSubSection id="A1D565563F67FFF0FF26FA3BFA9EF84A" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F67FFF0FF26FA3BFC63F96A" blockId="82.[151,1436,1433,1964]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
Morphology. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F67FFF0FEBFFA3BFD8BFA36" bold="true" box="[350,619,1469,1495]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">D V + I,7–10; A I,9–10;</emphasis>
P 15–16 (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F67FFF0FD39FA3BFC82FA36" author="Miller, P. J." box="[728,866,1469,1495]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" pagination="53 - 88" refId="ref61330" refString="Miller, P. J. (1973) The identity of Gobius affinis Kolombatovic, with notes on the systematics and biology of Pomatoschistus pictus (Malm). Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale ' Giacomo Doria', 79, 53 - 88." type="journal article" year="1973">Miller 1973</bibRefCitation>
). Pedomorphic habitus. Body laterally compressed, slender compared to other gobies. Large lateral eyes, wide interorbital space. Mouth superior, oblique, tip of lower jaw reaching the horizontal level of pupil. Caudal peduncle slender, distinctly lower than body depth. The first dorsal fin about equal to or lower than second dorsal fin, with more or less rounded margin. Dorsal fins widely separate with a broad interdorsal space. Pelvic disc complete with anterior membrane. Caudal fin truncate to slightly emarginate. Scales present, but usually not visible on photographs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F67FFF0FF26F913FB4FF919" blockId="82.[151,1436,1433,1964]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F67FFF0FE68F913FC46F932" bold="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Body semitranslucent with 4 elongate black markings along vertebral column and a large, conspicuous, triangular black spot at the base of caudal fin</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F67FFF0FC54F93FFBEAF932" box="[949,1034,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="32.[151,250,804,828]" captionTargetBox="[344,1243,181,780]" captionTargetId="figure-19@32.[344,1243,181,780]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 30. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Pseudaphya ferreri. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Rijeka, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601663/files/figure.png" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). A series of small black dots along lower margin of posterior body; white superficial speckles and markings in variable amounts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F67FFF0FF26F887FD14F8FD" blockId="82.[151,1436,1433,1964]" box="[199,756,1793,1820]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
